San Francisco and the whole Silicon Valley are the strategic area of the United States. The Grand Princess ship docking in San Francisco Bay last night might have been contaminated with Covid-19 in its central air system and infect people on the ship. There are many dots to connect the contamination path. The ship belongs to the same Grand Princess company that had another Grand Princess cruise ship docking In Japan with Covid-19 infection. One person from the ship has passed away in the previous trip from Mexico to SF, but the ship continued to operate and take on more people who then mixed with the passengers and the cruise members on the previous trip with potential of having being infected with Covid-19; and now the ship brought back another 2000 people with high potential for being infected with Covid-19 from the same cruise members as well as from the ship's central air system and the contaminated environment on the ship.
Covid-19 can stay deep in the lower respiratory tract. The virus takes time to multiply and show up in the saliva and phlegm. The rapid test from throat swab or nose swab samples can have a risk of not being sensitive enough to pick up a very small number of the virus, given the test is new and haven't have enough data to validate the sensitivity and accuracy level of the test. Let's say, for example, the test has 10% false negative because of sensitivity and accuracy, meaning that 10% of people who have infections but the test shows negative. Chinese tests have higher levels of false negative. Chinese research papers stated that many people had the symptoms; however, the tests showed negative results while chest CT scan already showed infection patches in the lungs.
Will the government be willing to take the high risk of creating infection crisis in the Silicon Valley later if allowing 2000 people on the ship to disembark in San Francisco Bay? The Australian government has allowed travelers with potential for infection to stay on isolated islands but not in the main land. Should we let the ship dock in an uncrowded, economically non-strategic place?
